    "body": "Ok, I see where it used (spark.SparkInstance#exception):\n\n``` java\n    public synchronized void exception(Class<? extends Exception> exceptionClass, ExceptionHandler handler) {\n        // wrap\n        ExceptionHandlerImpl wrapper = new ExceptionHandlerImpl(exceptionClass) {\n            @Override\n            public void handle(Exception exception, Request request, Response response) {\n                handler.handle(exception, request, response);\n            }\n        };\n\n        ExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, wrapper);\n    }\n```\n\nIn java8 it can be done in more elegant way, smth like\n\n``` java\nExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, () -> handler.handle(exception, request, response));\n```\n\nso ExceptionHandlerImpl can be safely removed, although it will be breaking change\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2016-03-08T14:34:53Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-03-08T14:39:47Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Ok, I see where it used (spark.SparkInstance#exception):\n\n``` java\n    public synchronized void exception(Class<? extends Exception> exceptionClass, ExceptionHandler handler) {\n        // wrap\n        ExceptionHandlerImpl wrapper = new ExceptionHandlerImpl(exceptionClass) {\n            @Override\n            public void handle(Exception exception, Request request, Response response) {\n                handler.handle(exception, request, response);\n            }\n        };\n\n        ExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, wrapper);\n    }\n```\n\nIn java8 it can be done in more elegant way, smth like\n\n``` java\nExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, () -> handler.handle(exception, request, response));\n```\n\nso ExceptionHandlerImpl can be safely removed, although it will be breaking change\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Ok, I see where it used (spark.SparkInstance#exception):\n\n``` java\n    public synchronized void exception(Class<? extends Exception> exceptionClass, ExceptionHandler handler) {\n        // wrap\n        ExceptionHandlerImpl wrapper = new ExceptionHandlerImpl(exceptionClass) {\n            @Override\n            public void handle(Exception exception, Request request, Response response) {\n                handler.handle(exception, request, response);\n            }\n        };\n\n        ExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, wrapper);\n    }\n```\n\nIn java8 it can be done in more elegant way, smth like\n\n``` java\nExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, () -> handler.handle(exception, request, response));\n```\n\nso ExceptionHandlerImpl can be safely removed, although it will be breaking change\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2016-03-08T14:34:53Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-03-08T14:39:47Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Ok, I see where it used (spark.SparkInstance#exception):\n\n``` java\n    public synchronized void exception(Class<? extends Exception> exceptionClass, ExceptionHandler handler) {\n        // wrap\n        ExceptionHandlerImpl wrapper = new ExceptionHandlerImpl(exceptionClass) {\n            @Override\n            public void handle(Exception exception, Request request, Response response) {\n                handler.handle(exception, request, response);\n            }\n        };\n\n        ExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, wrapper);\n    }\n```\n\nIn java8 it can be done in more elegant way, smth like\n\n``` java\nExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, () -> handler.handle(exception, request, response));\n```\n\nso ExceptionHandlerImpl can be safely removed, although it will be breaking change\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "updated_at": "2016-03-08T14:39:47Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Ok, I see where it used (spark.SparkInstance#exception):\n\n``` java\n    public synchronized void exception(Class<? extends Exception> exceptionClass, ExceptionHandler handler) {\n        // wrap\n        ExceptionHandlerImpl wrapper = new ExceptionHandlerImpl(exceptionClass) {\n            @Override\n            public void handle(Exception exception, Request request, Response response) {\n                handler.handle(exception, request, response);\n            }\n        };\n\n        ExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, wrapper);\n    }\n```\n\nIn java8 it can be done in more elegant way, smth like\n\n``` java\nExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, () -> handler.handle(exception, request, response));\n```\n\nso ExceptionHandlerImpl can be safely removed, although it will be breaking change\n",

    "updated_at": "2016-03-08T14:39:47Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Ok, I see where it used (spark.SparkInstance#exception):\n\n``` java\n    public synchronized void exception(Class<? extends Exception> exceptionClass, ExceptionHandler handler) {\n        // wrap\n        ExceptionHandlerImpl wrapper = new ExceptionHandlerImpl(exceptionClass) {\n            @Override\n            public void handle(Exception exception, Request request, Response response) {\n                handler.handle(exception, request, response);\n            }\n        };\n\n        ExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, wrapper);\n    }\n```\n\nIn java8 it can be done in more elegant way, smth like\n\n``` java\nExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, () -> handler.handle(exception, request, response));\n```\n\nso ExceptionHandlerImpl can be safely removed, although it will be breaking change\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2016-03-08T14:34:53Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-03-08T14:39:47Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Ok, I see where it used (spark.SparkInstance#exception):\n\n``` java\n    public synchronized void exception(Class<? extends Exception> exceptionClass, ExceptionHandler handler) {\n        // wrap\n        ExceptionHandlerImpl wrapper = new ExceptionHandlerImpl(exceptionClass) {\n            @Override\n            public void handle(Exception exception, Request request, Response response) {\n                handler.handle(exception, request, response);\n            }\n        };\n\n        ExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, wrapper);\n    }\n```\n\nIn java8 it can be done in more elegant way, smth like\n\n``` java\nExceptionMapper.getInstance().map(exceptionClass, () -> handler.handle(exception, request, response));\n```\n\nso ExceptionHandlerImpl can be safely removed, although it will be breaking change\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "body": "The PR introduces done(..) but it is being executed before MatcherFilter is truly done. I kept a couple of code lines afterwards because it seemed to make sense :\r\n\r\n```\r\n        } finally {\r\n            try {\r\n                DoneFilters.execute(context);\r\n            } catch (Exception generalException) {\r\n                GeneralError.modify(\r\n                        httpRequest,\r\n                        httpResponse,\r\n                        body,\r\n                        requestWrapper,\r\n                        responseWrapper,\r\n                        generalException);\r\n            }\r\n        }\r\n\r\n        if (body.isSet()) {\r\n            body.serializeTo(httpResponse, serializerChain, httpRequest);\r\n        } else if (chain != null) {\r\n            chain.doFilter(httpRequest, httpResponse);\r\n        }\r\n    } //End of MatcherFilter.doFilter()\r\n```",

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Yes, this fixed an issue I encountered. Specifically, the [Rial](http://www.fileformat.info/info/unicode/char/fdfc/index.htm) character () was displaying properly in Word using an appropriate ASCII font (Tahoma) and the Chinese Yuan () was properly displaying in an East Asia font (Arial Unicode MS). However, when converting to PDF, docx is using the East Asia font for characters in this PR's range, including the Rial character, so it displays as a # sign (per fop's logic). It should be using the ASCII font for the Rial, as specified in the Microsoft documentation. \n\nIf I set the both the ASCII and East Asia fonts to Tahoma, the Rial works (though the Yuan doesn't, because Tahoma is not an appropriate East Asia font).\n",

    "body": "> I note null vector and offset vector are not included. For a column full of nulls, the estimated in memory size will be 0, although its actual in memory size is non-trivial. Just want do double check this is by design. Similarly, hash table in MapBlock is excluded from estimated in memory size.\r\n\r\nThe internal structure of an array may be changed over the time, and it may be different across different systems. The idea is to apply correction on planing time. Thats something that we already do for varchar blocks. \r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/prestodb/presto/blob/36e701b567c45e984828eaa067d2da83d2ae1217/presto-main/src/main/java/com/facebook/presto/cost/PlanNodeStatsEstimate.java#L93-L99\r\n\r\n> Let's make one commit for the two hidden aggregation functions, and explain the usage of these aggregation functions in commit message.\r\n\r\n+1",

  {
    "url": "https://api.github.com/repos/prestodb/presto/issues/comments/323800658",
    "html_url": "https://github.com/prestodb/presto/pull/8772#issuecomment-323800658",
    "issue_url": "https://api.github.com/repos/prestodb/presto/issues/8772",
    "id": 323800658,
    "node_id": "MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDMyMzgwMDY1OA==",
    "user": {
      "login": "wenleix",
      "id": 799346,
      "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjc5OTM0Ng==",
      "avatar_url": "https://avatars1.githubusercontent.com/u/799346?v=4",
      "gravatar_id": "",
      "url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix",
      "html_url": "https://github.com/wenleix",
      "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/followers",
      "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/following{/other_user}",
      "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/gists{/gist_id}",
      "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/starred{/owner}{/repo}",
      "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/subscriptions",
      "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/orgs",
      "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/repos",
      "events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/events{/privacy}",
      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/wenleix/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "created_at": "2017-08-21T17:08:22Z",
    "updated_at": "2020-02-24T22:23:23Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "There are two (theoretic) issues with the previous implementation:\r\n\r\nFirst, Java Language Specification doesn't guarantee atomic operation, in fact: \r\n\r\n> Programmers are encouraged to declare shared 64-bit values as volatile or synchronize their programs correctly to avoid possible complications.\r\n\r\nAlthough, the spec also says \r\n\r\n> Implementations of the Java Virtual Machine are encouraged to avoid splitting 64-bit values where possible.\r\n\r\n\r\nSecond, the previous implementation will read the instance field `sizeInBytes` twice, which is in theory problematic according to the Java memory model.\r\n\r\nWhen the first read returns >0, the two reads are not tied in any ordering constraints, as there is no intervening writes between them. Thus it does not violate JMM to returns -1 on the second read.\r\n\r\nMarking it as volatile solve both problems. For the second issue, sequentially consistent is guaranteed  for synchronization actions in JMM.\r\n\r\n\r\nReference: \r\n- http://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-17.html#jls-17.7\r\n- https://shipilev.net/blog/2016/close-encounters-of-jmm-kind/#wishful-benign-is-resilient\r\n- https://shipilev.net/blog/2014/jmm-pragmatics/#_synchronization_order\r\n- https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TxqsKzxyySo&index=1&list=PLk-F_TeGx1jxX9HeIdvWkxR0t5lH-iBQL&t=572s\r\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  }
]

    "body": "I think we might need this for SQL extension functions, too.\n\nGreatest is working as intended. Given null means unknown, you can't say something is greatest because the unknown might be greater. This the result is unknown. This is the same behavior as Oracle.\n\nYou could argue the other way, as PostgreSQL does, but that is less consistent with everything else in the language.\n\nWe could also ask the SQL spec committee what the expected behavior would be if this were standardized.\n",

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I think we might need this for SQL extension functions, too.\n\nGreatest is working as intended. Given null means unknown, you can't say something is greatest because the unknown might be greater. This the result is unknown. This is the same behavior as Oracle.\n\nYou could argue the other way, as PostgreSQL does, but that is less consistent with everything else in the language.\n\nWe could also ask the SQL spec committee what the expected behavior would be if this were standardized.\n",

    "body": "> I'm not sure, but I see that nameMapping is queried, while internalNameMaping is being written to (with registerX.\n> This in the tests works, but I think you mean to always query and register on the nameMapping.\n> \n> Am I correct?\n\n@Shredder121 _internalNameMapping_ is used for backward compatibility. All _register*_ functions use this variable. The _nameMapping_ variable allows contains\n- the same as _internalNameMapping_ if the programmer did not set a dynamic name mapping\n- a chained nameMapping that first checks _internalNameMapping_ and than falls back to the nameMapping provided by the programmer\n\nTherefore query is done always on _nameMapping_ while register\\* functions are applied to _internalNameMapping_. If I were you, I would remove the _register*_ functions and the _internalNameMapping_ from Querydsl 5.0.0 to have a cleaner API.\n",

      "received_events_url": "https://api.github.com/users/balazs-zsoldos/received_events",
      "type": "User",
      "site_admin": false
    },
    "created_at": "2016-11-16T20:18:28Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-11-16T20:18:28Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "If I need some discussions about the use-cases why I think this would be useful, please let me know.\n\nHowever, the exact issue that forced me to create the patch:\n- PostgreSQL quotes column names if _connection.prepareSatement(sql, columnNames[]) are called no matter what. See: https://www.postgresql.org/message-id/CAHEBw=SPKrZz=R7038UmGw9UZAuA7ejm0WA_tmMJ0Uv82-e8mg@mail.gmail.com\n- On the other hand, the same function works with Oracle only if the table and column names are created with upper-case letters. This is true by default, if the database tables and column names are populated without quotes\n\nWe could have a solution to create all table names always with quoted upper-case, but we provide [OpenSource solutions](https://github.com/everit-org/jira-querydsl-support) to database of third party apps like Jira. These databases are populated without quotes on object names, that means the object names have lower-case in PostgreSQL and upper-case in Oracle.\n\nWe cannot make our code database independent, only if we always use quoting and always with the default letter-case of the database. That is not possible with the current Querydsl version, only if we specify every table and column name within the Configuration instance manually.\n\nI think true database independent code can be written only if the programmer has the possibility to specify rules like: Generate SQL statements with quoted object names with converted to upper-case (or lower-case).\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },
  {

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Taking a brief glance at this it looks as though the table/column names are the same as in the objc binding, but there is differing logic in how/when rows are added to the primary key table. Because of this there will most likely be issues when accessing Realm files created on other platforms.\n\nI think the only way to truly ensure compatibility is to come up with a proper file format spec for the object store, and ideally have a common code path for reading and writing all object store metadata. Even when only looking at a single platform having a versioned file format will be a necessity in order to support sync properly.\n",

    "body": "I have reverted all styles to our usual standard until we decide otherwise. Logic for primary keys has been verified to be similar to iOS, most importantly is automatic migrations when loading the schemas. I have tested that Realms can be read from iOS, but cannot merge that in until we decide on how to do custom schema support. Code paths are different for manipulating meta tables are different, but unless we move that into a shared C++ library that can't be helped. \n- copyOrUpdate() and createOrUpdateFromJson() methods are being worked on in a separate PR (soon done).\n- Auto incremental keys are also in another PR, pending further discussion. I still strongly think they should be included, but should probably be marked as \"local\". Ie. not allowed in databases used in sync scenarios. For sync we probably need to put restrictions on schema changes anyway, disallowing auto incremental keys would be easy in that case.\n\nReady for 2nd round: @kneth @emanuelez @bmunkholm @alazier \n",

    "body": "Ready for review: @emanuelez @bmunkholm @kneth \n\nSome discussion points:\n- Non-managed RealmLists can also hold managed lists. They will be ignored if they are copied to the same Realm again, but used if copied to another Realm. The first draft didn't allow them at all, but this is more convenient i think? \n- Is copyToRealm the proper name. I like addToRealm() more. It is the same as iOS and no matter what, people will need to learn not to use the standalone objects after they have been added. copyToRealm might make it more apparent though?\n- Return type for copyToRealm(Iterable). Right now it is Collection, but collections doesn't support .get(index) and adapters usually require List, not Collections. Also the implementation is actually an ArrayList. I think that returning List will cater for more standard use cases? thoughts?\n",

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Ready for review: @emanuelez @bmunkholm @kneth \n\nSome discussion points:\n- Non-managed RealmLists can also hold managed lists. They will be ignored if they are copied to the same Realm again, but used if copied to another Realm. The first draft didn't allow them at all, but this is more convenient i think? \n- Is copyToRealm the proper name. I like addToRealm() more. It is the same as iOS and no matter what, people will need to learn not to use the standalone objects after they have been added. copyToRealm might make it more apparent though?\n- Return type for copyToRealm(Iterable). Right now it is Collection, but collections doesn't support .get(index) and adapters usually require List, not Collections. Also the implementation is actually an ArrayList. I think that returning List will cater for more standard use cases? thoughts?\n",
